Seminar in Jazz Studies
Jazz and Film
JAZZ G6200y: (John Szwed) R 4:10-6. Seminar limited to 16 students. An =
examination of the use, representation and influence of jazz on film, =
including shorts, cartoons, soundies, documentaries, and features by =
Malle, Scorsese, Minnelli, Altman, Lee, Kar-wei, and others. Call # =
22796    <>

To apply: email Prof. Szwed (jfs54@columbia.edu) with basic data (major, =
year of undergraduate study, relevant courses taken), plus a brief =
statement about your interest in the course and what you think you could =
contribute to the seminar.=20
Although primarily a graduate seminar, Prof. Szwed will accept several =
qualified undergraduates into the course (please note that this class =
may not be used toward the English major, nor does it satisfy any =
distribution requirements).

  Prof. John Szwed's Bio
Szwed has been at Yale University since 1982, where he is John M. Musser =
Professor of Anthropology, African-American Studies, Music, and Film =
Studies, Yale University, and where he has served as Director of =
Graduate Studies in Anthropology and Acting Chair of African-American =
Studies. In addition, he has also been Louis Armstrong Visiting =
Professor of Jazz Studies at Columbia University for several years.  =
Szwed is President and producer for the non-profit music production =
company Brilliant Corners, which is based in New York City. =20
Szwed holds an M.A. in Communications and a Ph.D. in Sociology and =
Antropology from The Ohio State University. His research and teaching =
have garnered him national recognition, including fellowships from the =
Guggenheim and Rockefeller foundations. In addition to numerous =
publications ranging from anthropological studies of Newfoundland to =
liner notes for Impulse and Riverside Records, Szwed's has recently =
published several books relating to jazz, Space is the Place: The Life =
and Times of Sun Ra (1997); Jazz 101 ( 2000); The Future of Jazz (with =
Greg Tate, et al.) (2002 ); So What: The Life of Miles Davis (2002); =
Crossovers: Essays on Race, Music, and American Culture (2005); Doctor =
Jazz in  Jelly Roll Morton: The Complete Library of Congress Recordings =
by Alan Lomax (2005); Blues for New Orleans: Ptasie Song for Mardi Gras =
and America's Creole Soul (with Robert Farris Thompson, Roger Abrahams, =
and Nichola Spitzer) (2006).  He also write scripts for Jazz in  the =
Schools, used in the National Endowment for the Arts/Jazz at Lincoln =
Center project (2005), and is at work on a biography of folklorist Alan =
Lomax.
